(abstract)
Suppose that we have a number of good solutions to a job shop scheduling 
problem and are interested in finding a lower bound.  We modify the shaving 
algorithm, a lower bound technique dus to Martin and Shmoys, in order to take 
advantage of the information contained in the solutions. Given these good 
solutions, our approach is up to three times faster than Martin and Shmoys' 
algorithm.  In the worst case, our approach was only slightly slower.
In addition, we found new lower bounds to some open benchmark instances:
